{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180911154829|859080637","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Buddy_Carter","to":"Buddy Carter"}],"pages":{"39805284":{"pageid":39805284,"ns":0,"title":"Buddy Carter","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-24T19:27:05Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{use American English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Buddy Carter\n|image         = Buddy Carter, Official Portrait, 114th Congress.jpg \n|state         = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|district      = {{ushr|GA|1|1st}}\n|term_start    = January 3, 2015\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Jack Kingston]]\n|successor     = \n|state_senate1 = Georgia\n|district1     = 1st\n|term_start1   = 2009\n|term_end1     = 2014\n|predecessor1  = [[Eric Johnson (Georgia politician)|Eric Johnson]]\n|successor1    = Ben Watson\n|state_house2  = Georgia\n|district2     = 159th\n|term_start2   = 2005\n|term_end2     = 2009\n|predecessor2  = ???\n|successor2    = Ann Purcell\n|birth_name    = Earl Leroy Carter\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1957|9|6}}\n|birth_place   = [[Port Wentworth, Georgia]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education     = [[Young Harris College]]<br>[[University of Georgia]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])\n}}\n'''Earl Leroy \"Buddy\" Carter'''  (born September 6, 1957) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. representative]] for [[Georgia's 1st congressional district]]. Previously, he was a member of the [[Georgia State Senate|Georgia state senate]].<ref name=\"sgagov\"><span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.senate.ga.gov/senators/en-US/member.aspx?Member=778&Session=23 Senator Buddy Carter]</span>. Senate.ga.gov. Retrieved June 28, 2013.</ref> Carter was first elected as a state senator in the 2009 [[general election]].<ref><span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.senate.ga.gov/senators/en-US/District.aspx?District=1&Session=23 District 1 Senator Buddy Carter (R)]</span>. Senate.ga.gov. Retrieved June 28, 2013.</ref>\nHe is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nCarter graduated from Robert W. Groves High School, in 1975, in [[Garden City, Georgia]].{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} He earned an [[associate degree]] from [[Young Harris College]], in 1977 and a [[Bachelor of Science]], in [[pharmacy]], from the [[University of Georgia]], in 1980.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Political career==\nCarter served on the planning and zoning commission for the city of [[Pooler, Georgia|Pooler]] from 1989 to 1993 and on Pooler's city council from 1994 to 1995. Carter served as Pooler's mayor from 1996 to 2004 as well. Carter was first elected to the state legislature in 2005\u2014serving two terms in the [[Georgia House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] from 2006 to 2010. Carter was elected to the [[Georgia Senate]] in 2009 and sworn into the [[upper house]] in 2010.<ref name=\"sgagov\"/> He sat on the Senate [[Appropriations Committee (Georgia Senate)|Appropriations]], [[Health and Human Services Committee (Georgia Senate)|Health and Human Services]], [[Higher Education Committee (Georgia Senate)|Higher Education]], and [[Public Safety Committee (Georgia Senate)|Public Safety]] committees.<ref name=\"sgagov\"/>\n\nIn March 2014, a controversy emerged regarding S.B. 408, a bill authored by Carter that would increase reimbursement rates for pharmacies in Georgia. As he is the owner of three pharmacies which would see increased profits as a result of the proposed action, his vote was considered by many to be in violation of the ethical guidelines of the State Senate. \"Obviously, it's borderline,\" he admitted when questioned afterwards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zpolitics.com/i-team-investigates-pharmacy-bill-carried-sen-buddy-carter/|title=Squarespace - Claim This Domain|website=zpolitics.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref>\n\nCarter gave up his state house seat in 2014 to make a run for Congress after 22-year incumbent [[Jack Kingston]] announced he was running for the [[United States Senate]]. He finished first in the six-way Republican primary with 36 percent of the vote, well short of the 51 percent required for outright victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=787452|title=Our Campaigns - GA District 01 - R Primary Race - May 20, 2014|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> He then defeated Bob Johnson in the runoff with 53 percent of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=795586|title=Our Campaigns - GA District 01 - R Runoff Race - Jul 22, 2014|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> In the general election, he trounced his Democratic challenger, Brian Reese, with 60.9 percent of the vote, carrying all but two counties in the district.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=782780|title=Our Campaigns - GA - District 01 Race - Nov 04, 2014|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> In 2016, he was unopposed in both the primary and general elections, and took over 99 percent of the vote against a write-in candidate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=806161|title=Our Campaigns - GA District 01 - R Primary Race - May 24, 2016|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=801571|title=Our Campaigns - GA District 01 Race - Nov 08, 2016|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n=== Drug policy ===\nThe marijuana legalization advocacy organization [[National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws|NORML]] has rated Carter a \"D\", which indicates a strongly anti-drug stance.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/georgia|title=Georgia Scorecard - NORML.org - Working to Reform Marijuana Laws|last=Laura|website=norml.org|language=en-us|access-date=2017-08-12}}</ref>\n\nCarter voted against the Veterans Equal Access Amendment in 2015 & 2016 (which would expand access to medical marijuana for veterans), against the McClintock/Polis Amendment in 2015 (which would prevent the Department of Justice from prosecuting federal marijuana offenses that are legal in the state) and against the Rohrabacher/Farr Amendment in 2015 (which would prevent federal officials from interfering with a state's medical marijuana program).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2017, Carter renewed his push to drug test citizens who receive unemployment insurance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/07/20/buddy-carter-looks-to-drug-test-recipients-of-unemployment-benefits/|title=Buddy Carter looks to drug test recipients of unemployment benefits {{!}} Political Insider blog|access-date=2017-08-12}}</ref>\n\n===Health care===\n\nCarter supports the repeal of the [[Affordable Care Act]] (ACA). He has stated that there is no circumstance that would induce him to vote in favor of keeping the ACA, including if most of his constituents were in favor of it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wjcl.com/article/fight-shouting-matches-mar-congressmans-town-hall-at-armstrong-state/8962093|title=Rep. Buddy Carter addresses residents at town hall|last=Christian|first=Ansley|date=2017-02-22|work=WJCL|access-date=2017-02-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2017, Carter was asked during a live television interview if he supported Trump's criticism of Republican U.S. Senator [[Lisa Murkowski]] for her opposition to the procedural vote to begin the Senate's healthcare debate. Carter agreed with the criticism, saying, \"Somebody needs to go over there to that Senate and snatch a knot in their ass.\"<ref>[http://thehill.com/homenews/house/343970-gop-rep-responds-to-female-senators-vote-against-repeal-snatch-a-knot-in-their GOP lawmaker on Murkowski: 'Snatch a knot in their ass'] Julia Manchester. The Hill. July 26, 2017. Retrieved July 28, 2017.</ref> The incident prompted widespread media coverage.<ref>[http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2017/07/27/_snatch_a_knot_in_their_ass_explained.html A Georgia Congressman Thinks the Senate Needs Someone to \u201cSnatch a Knot in Their A--.\u201d Um, What?] Ben Zimmer. Slate. July 27, 2017. Retrieved July 28, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://time.com/4875702/buddy-carter-snatch-a-knot-in-their-ass-lisa-murkowski/ 'Snatch a Knot in Their Ass': GOP Congressman Defends President Trump's Criticism of Sen. Lisa Murkowski] Aric Jenkins. Time. July 26, 2017. Retrieved July 28, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.marketwatch.com/story/suddenly-everyone-is-snatching-a-knot-and-heres-why-2017-07-26 How Congressman Buddy Carter got the whole country looking up the phrase \u2018snatch a knot\u2019] Tim Rostan. MarketWatch. July 27, 2017. Retrieved July 28, 2017.</ref>\n\n=== Tax reform ===\n\nCarter voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=25 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> His reason for voting \"Yea\" on the bill was that he believed businesses located in his district would become more competitive in a global market. He also said it would help his constituents earn and/or save more money.<ref name=\"WTOC121917\">{{cite web|title=Rep. Buddy Carter reacts to tax reform bill initially passing the House|url=http://www.wtoc.com/story/37102660/rep-buddy-carter-reacts-to-tax-reform-bill-initially-passing-the-house|website=WTOC|accessdate=25 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\n\nCarter has stated that \"granting amnesty to illegal immigrants is unconstitutional.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buddycarter.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=1089|title=Carter Statement on United States v. Texas Decision|date=2016-06-23|website=Congressman Buddy Carter|access-date=2017-08-12}}</ref> However, he has co-sponsored a bill which would let illegal immigrants serve in the US military in exchange for legal residency.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bulloch.allongeorgia.com/congressman-buddy-carter-co-sponsors-military-immigration-bill-for-illegals/|title=Congressman Buddy Carter co-sponsors military immigration bill for illegals {{!}} All On Georgia Bulloch County|last=Spencer|first=Jeremy|date=2017-06-07|work=All On Georgia Bulloch County|access-date=2017-08-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nCarter supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to temporarily curtail immigration from six countries until better screening methods are devised. He stated that \"While I believe there needs to be thoughtful clarifications on the executive actions similar to Secretary Kelly\u2019s announcement about lawful permanent residents, the number one priority of the federal government is to provide for the common defense.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban/|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump\u2019s travel ban; here\u2019s where the rest stand|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|website=Denver Post|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCarter wants to prohibit all federal funding from [[Sanctuary city|sanctuary cities]] in Georgia (sanctuary cities prohibit city officials from asking about a person's immigration status when they're reporting an unrelated crime).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thebrunswicknews.com/news/local_news/rep-carter-takes-aim-at-sanctuary-cities/article_c17ca3db-7742-52c6-9cba-3c6a303a79e5.html|title=Rep. Carter takes aim at 'sanctuary cities'|work=The Brunswick News|access-date=2017-08-12|language=en}}</ref> Carter also stated he would like to test the huge backlog of rape kits in Georgia, except in sanctuary cities. He said about testing the rape kit backlog, \"We'll do everything we can to help,\" but then added, \"Unless they\u2019re a sanctuary city.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://theslot.jezebel.com/gop-rep-buddy-carter-well-help-clear-rape-kit-backlog-1797752964|title=GOP Rep. Buddy Carter: We'll Help Clear Rape Kit Backlogs 'Unless They're a Sanctuary City'|last=Shechet|first=Ellie|work=The Slot|access-date=2017-08-12|language=en-US}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=May 2018}}\n\n=== Abortion ===\nCarter opposes abortion. He cosponsored the [[Sanctity of Human Life Act]] (H.R. 586), which would make all abortions illegal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buddycarter.house.gov/issues/issue/?IssueID=14891|title=Protecting Life : U.S. Representative Buddy Carter|website=buddycarter.house.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-08-12}}</ref>\n\nH.R. 586 provides a constitutional right to life to embryos at the moment of fertilization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/586|title=H.R. 586 - Sanctity of Human Life Act.|last=|first=|date=|website=Congress.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 26, 2017}}</ref> While a similar bill in the Senate, S. 231, claims to not target women who use birth control, women who suffer from miscarriages, or families that want to conceive using vitro fertilization,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/senate-bill/231/text|title=S.231 - Life at Conception Act of 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=Congress.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=February 26, 2017}}</ref> the House bill contains no such exceptions.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} When asked by a constituent during a town hall in Savannah, Georgia whether he had concerns about restricting access to birth control when rape is so common on college campuses, Carter replied \"I'm not going to vote for any bill that endorses abortion.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.connectsavannah.com/savannah/buddy-carter-town-hall-meeting-heavy-on-drama-and-volume-but-scant-on-specifics/Content?oid=4063681|title=Buddy Carter town hall heavy on drama and volume, but scant on specifics|last=Morekis|first=Jim|website=Connect Savannah|access-date=2017-02-26}}</ref> H.R. 586, which would ban abortion, contains no exceptions for the life or health of the mother or for cases of rape or incest.\n\n===Education===\n\nWhen questioned during a February 2017 town hall in Savannah, Georgia as to whether religious doctrine ought to be taught in public school science classes, Carter responded \"I have always thought we should teach the Bible in school.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://savannahnow.com/politics/news/2017-02-21/big-crowd-challenges-supports-buddy-carter-savannah-town-hall|title=Big crowd challenges, supports Buddy Carter at Savannah town hall|work=savannahnow.com|access-date=2017-02-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT rights===\n\nCarter believes gay marriage should be illegal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Buddy_Carter_Civil_Rights.htm|title=Buddy Carter on Civil Rights|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=2017-08-12}}</ref>\n\nDuring an August 2017 town hall in Brunswick, Georgia, Carter stated that he supported a ban on transgender people serving in the military, saying, \"I don't want 'em serving in the military. I'm sorry.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/08/11/buddy-carter-on-transgender-troops-i-dont-want-em-serving-in-the-military/|title=Buddy Carter on transgender troops: \u2018I don\u2019t want \u2019em serving\u2019 {{!}} Political Insider blog|last=Galloway|first=Jim|access-date=2017-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thegavoice.com/dont-want-em-georgia-congressman-praises-transgender-troop-ban-town-hall/|title=\u2018I don\u2019t want \u2019em:\u2019 Georgia congressman praises transgender troop ban at town hall|work=thegavoice.com/|access-date=2017-08-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Gun rights ===\n\nCarter is a strong supporter of gun rights, and has an \"A\" rating from the [[National Rifle Association]] for his stances on gun issues.\n\nIn 2018, Carter stated: \"I support the 2nd Amendment so I don't want to see us outlawing anything. However, however I will say that I have recently come out and said I am against bump stocks.\" Bump stocks are what allowed the shooter in the [[Las Vegas Massacre]] to convert some of his guns to automatic weapons. \"Automatic weapons are against the law here in America and a bump stock in my opinion is nothing more than an attempt to circumvent the law so I don't think that we should have those,\" said Carter.\n\n\"But you know at the same time people have the right to bear arms, it's the 2nd Amendment,\" Carter reiterated. \"And you know even if you were to outlaw some of these semi-automatic weapons they're going to get a get a weapon from somewhere,\" he said.\n\nIn February 2018 during a town hall in [[Hinesville, Georgia]] when asked about mass shootings in America, Carter told attendees to not look towards Congress for answers about gun violence, stating Congress is not responsible for gun violence in America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wsav.com/news/congressman-carter-on-2nd-amendment-and-semi-automatic-weapons/1077868597|title=Congressman Carter on 2nd Amendment and semi-automatic weapons {{!}} WSAV Savannah|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Bills introduced and signed into law==\n\nThe [[GAO Access and Oversight Act of 2017]] ({{USPL|115|3}},{{USBill|115|hr|72}}), which was one of the first [[List of Acts of the 115th United States Congress|Acts of the 115th United States Congress]] signed into law by President Trump during the first 100 days of his presidency, was introduced to the House by Carter on January 1, 2017. It passed through the [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs]] and was passed by the full Senate, on January 17, 2017. It was signed by Trump on January 31, 2017.<ref name=\"Sasse_T100_115-3\">{{citation |title=President Trump Signs Sasse Legislation to Strengthen Taxpayer Watchdog |url=https://www.sasse.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/2017/2/president-trump-signs-sasse-legislation-to-strengthen-taxpayer-watchdog |work=Office of [[Ben Sasse]]: U.S. Senator for Nebraska |location=Washington |date=February 2, 2017 |accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> The bill ensures that the [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) has full access to a database created by Congress in 1996 to track recent job hires mainly to assist agencies at the state level with child support enforcement. 115-3 will enable the GAO to ensure that recipients of federal means-tested programs like [[Unemployment benefits#United States|Unemployment Insurance]], [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program]] (SNAP), [[Earned income tax credit]] (EITC), and [[Temporary Assistance for Needy Families]] (TANF) are eligible.<ref name=\"115-3\">{{cite web | url=https://www.isakson.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/2017/1/isakson-perdue-take-action-to-increase-government-transparency-accountability | title=Senators Isakson, Perdue take action to increase government transparency and accountability | work=Office of Senator Isakson | date=January 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Public_now_115-3\">{{citation |url=http://www.publicnow.com/view/600CF9E9B80D646D3091332D94DB698F8D89B508?2017-01-19-00:00:28+00:00-xxx9728 | date=January 19, 2017 |accessdate=March 28, 2017 |title=McCaskill-Backed Bill Reducing Government Waste and Increasing Accountability Unanimously Passes Senate |work=Office of [[Claire McCaskill]]}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Health]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Environment|Subcommittee on Environment]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n{{Portal|State of Georgia}}\n*\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=|date=|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[House Baltic Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|format=|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|date=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Buddy Carter}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://buddycarter.house.gov/ Congressman Buddy Carter] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.buddycarterforcongress.com/ Buddy Carter for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Buddy_Carter_%5BR-1%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|buddycarter}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=C001103 | votesmart=32085 | fec=H4GA01039 | congress=earl-carter/2236 }}<!-- Links fo